04754nam a22006735i 9780271088259DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710882597 a10.1515/97802710882592doi  a(DE-B1597)584414  a(OCoLC)1227386800  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN1590.A54bM35 2021eb 7aTEC0010002bisacsh04a7912231 aMcQuinn, Austin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBecoming Audible :bSounding Animality in Performance /cAustin McQuinn. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnimalibus: Of Animals and Cultures ;v1800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 Becoming Audible: Listening in Between Species -- t2 Becoming Acoustic: Concealing and Revealing Voices in Hunting and Performance Interactions -- t3 Becoming Botched: Play, Tactical Empathy, and Neo-Shamanic Acoustic Legacies in Performance -- t4 Becoming Canine: The Scandal of the Singing Animal Body -- t5 Becoming Lingual: Primate Trouble in the Academy of Speech -- t6 Becoming Resonant: Sounding the Creatural Through Performance -- tCoda -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBecoming Audible explores the phenomenon of human and animal acoustic entanglements in art and performance practices. Focusing on the work of artists who get into the spaces between species, Austin McQuinn discovers that sounding animality secures a vital connection to the creatural.To frame his analysis, McQuinn employs Gilles Deleuze and Félix Guattari's concept of becoming-animal, Donna Haraway's definitions of multispecies becoming-with, and Mladen Dolar's ideas of voice-as-object. McQuinn considers birdsong in the work of Beatrice Harrison, Olivier Messiaen, Céleste Boursier-Mougenot, Daniela Cattivelli, and Marcus Coates; the voice of the canine as a sacrificial lab animal in the operatic work of Alexander Raskatov; hierarchies of vocalization in human-simian cultural coevolution in theatrical adaptations of Franz Kafka and Eugene O'Neill; and the acoustic exchanges among hybrid human-animal creations in Harrison Birtwistle's opera The Minotaur. Inspired by the operatic voice and drawing from work in art and performance studies, animal studies, zooarchaeology, social and cultural anthropology, and philosophy, McQuinn demonstrates that sounding animality in performance resonates "through the labyrinths of the cultural and the creatural," not only across species but also beyond the limits of the human.Timely and provocative, this volume outlines new methods of unsettling human exceptionalism during a period of urgent reevaluation of interspecies relations. Students and scholars of human-animal studies, performance studies, and art historians working at the nexus of human and animal will find McQuinn's book enlightening and edifying.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnimal sounds. 0aHuman-animal relationships in art. 0aHuman-animal relationships in the performing arts. 0aPerformance art. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Acoustics & Sound.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271088259zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271088259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271088259.jpg  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPA